# UDS Factory Versioning

The factory build version answers one question: "was this component
built under the current factory's output bar, or an older one?" It is
the factory's **vintage** — the date its output last changed — stamped
onto every component the factory builds. It is NOT the component's build
date (that's `built_at`).

## Three version axes — do not conflate

| Axis | Lives in | Bumps when |
|---|---|---|
| `lastUpdated` (per file) | each rule/skill/agent frontmatter | the file is edited at all |
| Contract format version (`v1`) | the `<<UDS-FACTORY-CONTRACT>>` delimiter | the block's parsable shape changes |
| **Factory build version** (`YYYY.MM.DD.N`) | `.cursor/figma/state/factory-version.json` | the factory's OUTPUT changes |

Format-version (`v1`) policy: adding a contract-block section is additive
(readers tolerate a missing section), so it stays `v1`; only a breaking
re-shape bumps to `v2`.

## When to bump the build version

Bump when a change to any factory file —
[`generate-uds-figma-component/SKILL.md`](../skills/generate-uds-figma-component/SKILL.md),
[`uds-figma-factory-quality.mdc`](./uds-figma-factory-quality.mdc),
[`uds-figma-plugin-api-gotchas.mdc`](./uds-figma-plugin-api-gotchas.mdc),
[`uds-design-language.mdc`](./uds-design-language.mdc), or
[`uds-naming-conventions.mdc`](./uds-naming-conventions.mdc) — changes
what a factory run PRODUCES:

- a new or changed Phase C quality gate
- a new construction pattern (focus ring, skeleton, …)
- a new or changed contract-block section
- a changed default (emphasis, glyph, token-binding policy)
- a changed variant-axis convention

(`uds-design-language` and `uds-naming-conventions` are in this rule's
globs so editing them surfaces this reminder — but they're broad rules;
bump only when the edit actually changes factory output, not for an
unrelated tweak.)

Each such change mints a new `YYYY.MM.DD.N` (increment `N` for a second
output change the same day). The number is chronological — mark the
changelog entry `breaking: true` for a removal / rename / contract-shape
change that can invalidate a prior draft, `false` for an additive
improvement. Severity lives in the flag, not the digits.

## When NOT to bump

Prose clarifications, typos, reordering, examples, or any edit that
leaves factory output identical. These bump `lastUpdated` only.

## How to bump

1. Set `version` in `.cursor/figma/state/factory-version.json` to a fresh
   `YYYY.MM.DD.N` (date from `date -u +%Y.%m.%d`).
2. Prepend a changelog entry (newest first): `version`, `date`
   (`date -u +%Y-%m-%d`), `breaking` (true/false), `affects[]` (anatomy
   tags, or `["all"]`), `summary` (plain-language, 1–2 sentences).
3. If the entry uses a NEW `affects[]` label, add it to the `labels` map
   (English meaning) AND add its detector to the drift pass.
4. The factory reads `version` at build time and stamps it (plugin data
   + contract-block `Factory-version:` line).

### Ordering: bump before you stamp

If your own pending change is what moves the bar (editing
`uds-naming-conventions.mdc`, a Phase C gate in
`uds-figma-factory-quality.mdc`, etc.), bump the version FIRST — in the
same commit as the factory-file edit (the CI audit requires this; see
"CI enforcement") — and only THEN stamp or re-stamp drafts, at the NEW
version. Stamping drafts at the old bar and bumping afterward means
re-stamping everything you just touched. That happened once: metric-card
/ combobox / toggle / stepper were stamped at `2026.06.07.1`, the naming
change then moved the bar, and all four had to be re-stamped to
`2026.06.08.1`. Decide the bar, then stamp.

## How `affects[]` matching works

`affects[]` entries are named labels (`nests-button`, `tone-axis`,
`all`, …). The `labels` map in `factory-version.json` is the
human-readable registry — what each label means. The matching is done by
the drift pass, which carries a real detector per label (keyed by name)
that reads the component's actual anatomy as `figma-component-inspector`
extracts it (nested instances, variant axes, states). Matching is exact,
not fuzzy. Adding a label = the `labels` entry AND its detector.

## How it's stamped and carried

- **Figma:** `setSharedPluginData('dsb','factory_version', <version>)` on
  the main component-set node (`udc-<id>`), plus a
  `Factory-version: <version>` line in the `<<UDS-FACTORY-CONTRACT>>`
  block. The stamp survives the designer's acceptance rename — it lives
  on the node, not the page name.
- **`built_at` vs `run_id`:** `built_at` is the date of the factory write
  that produced the current stamped state; `run_id` records the creation
  run (and is what cleanup tooling maps to). On a **stamp-only catch-up**
  (re-emit/upgrade, not a fresh build), bump `factory_version` to the
  current bar and `built_at` to the upgrade date, but **keep the original
  `run_id`** — do not mint a new one for an in-place upgrade. The three
  fields then read coherently: `run_id` = birth run, `built_at` = last
  factory write, `factory_version` = bar met.
- **Docs:** `sync-figma-component-spec` / `uds-updated` copies it into
  `spec.json` `provenance.factoryVersion`.

## Drift is reported, never auto-applied on a live component

A behind-version component is REPORTED. Upgrades follow the maintenance
loop, picking the lightest sufficient action:

- **Un-accepted `{Cursor}` drafts** — free write (scope #4). Prefer a
  **stamp-only catch-up** for the common case: an unstamped
  (pre-versioning) draft that audits as already-at-bar just needs the
  `factory_version` / `built_at` plugin data and the `Factory-version:`
  contract line — not a teardown. Apply scoped fixes only for the bar
  items that actually fail, then stamp. Full regenerate only when the
  draft is structurally behind or the designer asks. (Run the audit with
  the host-vs-nested attribution + structural ring-detection guards from
  [`uds-figma-plugin-api-gotchas.mdc`](./uds-figma-plugin-api-gotchas.mdc)
  §14–§15 so a nested component's own parts aren't misread as cruft.)
- **Live components** — review-gated inspect → diff → propose → approve,
  where NOTHING applies without per-change approval (additive and
  breaking alike).
- **`{Frozen}` components** — reported as behind, no writes at all.

The factory never silently rewrites (`uds-source-of-truth.mdc`).

## CI enforcement

`scripts/audit-factory-version-currency.sh` (wired into
`.github/workflows/audits.yml`) fails CI when a commit after the audit
baseline touches any of the five factory files above WITHOUT bumping
`.cursor/figma/state/factory-version.json` in the same commit. The escape
for a genuinely output-neutral edit (prose, typo, reordering,
audit/process-only) is a `[no-factory-bump: <reason>]` tag in the commit
message — same shape as `audit-changelog-currency.sh`'s `[no-changelog:
...]`. The audit can't judge whether output *actually* changed; it forces
the decision to be made in-commit and reviewed, instead of relying on the
author to remember it.

**Bump in the SAME commit as the factory-file edit.** A bump that lands one
commit later still trips the audit on the earlier commit (this rule + the
naming-convention change shipped that way once, in `9a14a58` then
`a96d0bd`, and is grandfathered by the baseline — don't repeat it).

## Editing this rule

Lives under `.cursor/rules/`, so
[`uds-rule-discipline.mdc`](./uds-rule-discipline.mdc) applies: bump
`lastUpdated:` and run `bash scripts/regenerate-toolchain.sh` when you
edit it, and keep its card on the Cursor Workflows Rules tab.

